Now I shall examine the high repute of the Vestals’ virginity, and the justice of its claim to be the standard for all the honour paid to purity. In the first place, they are taken in the tender years of childhood,b before a free choice of their own will, burning with zeal for the glory of chastity and love of their gods, can reject the lawful bonds of matri- mony. Their purity is taken prisoner and made over to thankless altars. In the poor girls the gratification of the body disappears not because it is seorned but because it is taken from them3 the body is kept immaculate, but not the mind, and there is no rest on a bed on which the unwedded woman sighs over a secret wound and the lost chance of marriage.
